A basis is a list of vectors in \(V\) that spans \(V\) and is linearly independent
constituents a LIST! of vectors in vector space \(V\) requirements the list is&hellip; linear independent spans \(V\) additional information criteria for basis A list \(v_1, \dots v_{n}\) of vectors in \(V\) is a basis of \(V\) IFF every \(v \in V\) can be written uniquely as:
\begin{equation} v = a_1v_1+ \dots + a_{n}v_{n} \end{equation}

Suppose \(v_1, \dots v_{n} \in V\) is a basis of some vector space \(V\); \(w_1, \dots w_{n} \in W\) is just a good&rsquo;ol list of length \(n= \dim V\) in \(W\).
There exists a unique linear map \(T \in \mathcal{L}(V,W)\) such that&hellip;
\begin{equation} Tv_{j} = w_{j} \end{equation}
for each \(j = 1, \dots n\)
Intuition The layperson&rsquo;s explanation of this result: 1) that, for everywhere you want to take the basis of one space, there&rsquo;s always a unique linear map to take you there.

