A function \(T: V\to W\) is surjective if its range equals its codomain \(W\). &ldquo;onto&rdquo;
&ldquo;For any possible output, \(w \in W\) for \(T \in \mathcal{L}(V,W)\), there is at LEAST one input \(T\) that maps \(Tv \to w\). &quot;
\begin{equation} \forall w \in W, \exists v \in V:Tv=W \end{equation}
map to bigger space is not surjective See map to bigger space is not surjective

For an operator \(T \in \mathcal{L}(V)\), \(T^{n}\) would make sense. Instead of writing \(TTT\dots\), then, we just write \(T^{n}\).
constituents operator \(T \in \mathcal{L}(V)\) requirements \(T^{m} = T \dots T\) additional information \(T^{0}\) \begin{equation} T^{0} := I \in \mathcal{L}(V) \end{equation}
\(T^{-1}\) \begin{equation} T^{-m} = (T^{-1})^{m} \end{equation}
if \(T\) is invertable
usual rules of squaring \begin{equation} \begin{cases} T^{m}T^{n} = T^{m+n} \\ (T^{m})^{n} = T^{mn} \end{cases} \end{equation}
This can be shown by counting the number of times \(T\) is repeated by writing each \(T^{m}\) out.

