Given what you claim as a normal distribution, we can test for its normality. Any distribution you claim as normal has to follow that:
\begin{equation} np \geq 10 &amp; n(1-p) \geq 10 \end{equation}
that number of successes and failures need both be greater than or equal to ten.

The Unreasonable Effectiveness of Mathematics in the Natural Sciences is an article by the famous mathematician Eugene Wigner. (Wigner 1990)
Reflection What I found most peculiarly interesting is the focus on many mathematical/physics texts on the idea of the &ldquo;beauty&rdquo; of the expressions; and, it seems, the clear pleasure that Wigner gets from analyzing the systems with the aforementioned &ldquo;beauty.&rdquo;
